  "text": "The Soon chamber was established to allow the real-time imaging of chemotaxis by carcinoma cells towards chemoattractants correlated with metastasis (Fig. 1G, Table 1 ) [CITATION_1] . It is similar to the pipette assay, but is modified to be able to provide steeper gradients. The Soon chamber assay consists of a micromanipulator which supports a micropipette filled with the chemoattractant of interest. Cells are grown on a coverslip which is placed in a glass-bottom dish, and the tip of the micropipette is placed approximately 20 μm below the coverslip top (near one of its edges) at an angle of 40 degrees from the vertical. The chemoattractant is continuously ejected from the micropipette. The coverslip acts as a dam and serves to increase the steepness of the gradient.",
